	(text_box "Calculated using this site: https://www.random-science-tools.com/electronics/schmitt-trigger-calculator.htm"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 195.58 255.27 0)
		(size 85.09 6.35)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type none)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "8faecf2e-ec23-4c8b-8a9d-6955d0e52a0b")
	)
	(text_box "Happily the RVQ040N has a fairly beefy body diode (forward voltage 1.2V, max pulsed current 10+ A). This provides some inbuilt ESD and flyback current protection on DIO, so if it goes above GND or below V_{LOGIC}, the voltage will be limited by the diode."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 194.31 83.82 0)
		(size 46.99 13.97)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type none)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "9dafd676-f249-48cf-9a5a-858e5b95ab96")
	)
	(text_box "RVQ040N has a drain-source resistance of 45 mΩ and a max current of 4 A. This means one channel can supply a great deal of current, and the current capacity of the DIO channels is limited by power supply constraints.\n- Per-channel limit: 4A source/sink\n- When running off internal power: Limited by internal rail capacity\n- When running off external power: Individual pins can reach 4A. Total power must not exceed connector and PCB trace limits."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 267.97 38.1 0)
		(size 54.61 24.13)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type none)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "a1a4fb7b-cb56-4565-8322-c61d665d074d")
	)
	(text_box "Schmitt trigger implemented using an LM311 open-collector comparator (basically the only part I could find that could work with 24V inputs).\nThis circuit provides hysterisis on the digital input, transitioning from low to high at 0.7x V_{LOGIC} and from high to low at 0.333x V_{LOGIC} (the ideal transition point would be 0.3x, but the 10k pullup on COMP_OUT skews this a bit).\nSadly this always produces an output with V_{LOGIC} voltage level so we need a secondary level shifter."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 167.64 234.95 0)
		(size 63.5 19.05)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type none)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "c0bc0f29-1e1a-4e49-9956-7ec69a6f78cc")
	)
	(text_box "To control the high and low output transistors, I selected an RT9624 gate driver chip. This chip uses an internal charge pump to generate a voltage of (VCC + PHASE) to control the upper transistor gate.\nThis chip has some neat features, including automatic shoot-through protection, so when switching, one transistor does not turn on until the gate of the other transistor has gone low.\nIt is controlled via a single tri-state line: pulling PWM high or low turns the upper or lower transistor on, while floating PWM keeps both transistors off. This avoids the need to use a second enable line!\nHowever, there are still a few things I might need to test out more:\n- This chip is technically a 5V device, with a logic high threshold of 2.3-3.2V. So, controlling it with a 3.3V logic line is possible, but a bit dicey. Need to make sure this doesn't cause an excessively long propagation time when turning off\n- The datasheet says it has resistors to pull the PWM line to a center voltage when not driven, but doesn't say what values these resistors are. So, I will also need to check the prop time of going from high and low to tri-state.\n- The datasheet example circuit puts a resistor in line with the VCC and BOOT pins, but doesn't say why. I copied this becase I assume there is some reason for it..."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 68.58 36.83 0)
		(size 81.28 48.26)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type none)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "ce22a563-6132-46e8-8f49-4df421c489a0")
	)
	(text_box "LM311 miniumum supply voltage is 3.5V, so if V_{LOGIC} is 3.3V, we need to give it more juice. Luckily it uses less than 10mA and the voltage drop isn't a big issue, so we can fix this with some diodes."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 186.69 170.18 0)
		(size 35.56 16.51)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type none)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "ce6519aa-ef13-4169-96c4-0193f2c6892a")
	)
	(text_box "The RVQ040N has a gate resistance of 7 ohms, so no gate resistor is needed with the RT9624. This should give a rise and fall time in the 10-20 ns range (between when the gate driver begins pumping current into the gate and when the MOSFET is fully on)."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 193.04 34.29 0)
		(size 44.45 15.24)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type none)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "d2875285-7bb7-4b98-9351-c2e9fb7f3145")
	)
